{
  "path": "java.dsa.arrays",
  "title": "Arrays in DSA",
  "section": "dsa",
  "difficulty": "beginner",
  "estimatedMins": 15,
  "tags": [
    "java",
    "dsa",
    "arrays",
    "sorting",
    "searching"
  ],
  "isDeepDive": false,
  "isPublished": true,
  "sortOrder": 1,
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "data": {
        "content": "An array is the most fundamental data structure — a fixed-size, contiguous block of memory holding elements of a single type. In Java, arrays are objects that live on the heap. Understanding array internals, common algorithms, and time complexity is the foundation of all DSA study."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "concept_cards",
      "data": {
        "items": [
          {
            "icon": "📏",
            "title": "Fixed Size",
            "desc": "Size is declared at creation and cannot change. new int[5] allocates exactly 5 elements. Use ArrayList for dynamic sizing."
          },
          {
            "icon": "0️⃣",
            "title": "Zero-based Index",
            "desc": "First element is [0], last is [length-1]. Accessing out of bounds throws ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException at runtime."
          },
          {
            "icon": "⚡",
            "title": "O(1) Access",
            "desc": "Random access by index is O(1) — elements are contiguous in memory. Address = base + (index × element_size)."
          },
          {
            "icon": "🔄",
            "title": "O(n) Insert",
            "desc": "Inserting or deleting in the middle requires shifting all subsequent elements — O(n) worst case."
          },
          {
            "icon": "🔲",
            "title": "2D Arrays",
            "desc": "int[][] grid = new int[3][4] — array of arrays. Rows can have different lengths (jagged arrays)."
          },
          {
            "icon": "🛠️",
            "title": "Arrays Utility",
            "desc": "Arrays.sort() O(n log n). Arrays.binarySearch() O(log n) on sorted. Arrays.fill(), copyOf(), toString()."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "diagram",
      "data": {
        "diagramKey": "java_dsa_array_complexity",
        "title": "Array Operations — Big-O",
        "diagramType": "mermaid",
        "mermaid": "graph LR\n  subgraph Array Operations\n    A[Access by index] -->|O-1| R1[Fastest]\n    B[Search unsorted] -->|O-n| R2[Linear scan]\n    C[Search sorted]   -->|O-logn| R3[Binary search]\n    D[Insert at end]   -->|O-1| R4[Amortized]\n    E[Insert middle]   -->|O-n| R5[Must shift]\n  end\n  style R1 fill:#166534,color:#fff\n  style R3 fill:#1d4ed8,color:#fff\n  style R4 fill:#166534,color:#fff\n  style R2 fill:#854d0e,color:#fff\n  style R5 fill:#991b1b,color:#fff"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "data": {
        "language": "java",
        "filename": "ArraysDSA.java",
        "runnable": true,
        "snippet": "import java.util.Arrays;\n\npublic class ArraysDSA {\n\n    // Linear Search -- O(n)\n    static int linearSearch(int[] arr, int target) {\n        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++)\n            if (arr[i] == target) return i;\n        return -1;\n    }\n\n    // Binary Search -- O(log n) -- array must be sorted\n    static int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {\n        int lo = 0, hi = arr.length - 1;\n        while (lo <= hi) {\n            int mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;\n            if      (arr[mid] == target) return mid;\n            else if (arr[mid] <  target) lo = mid + 1;\n            else                         hi = mid - 1;\n        }\n        return -1;\n    }\n\n    // Bubble Sort -- O(n^2)\n    static void bubbleSort(int[] arr) {\n        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length - 1; i++)\n            for (int j = 0; j < arr.length - 1 - i; j++)\n                if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {\n                    int tmp = arr[j]; arr[j] = arr[j+1]; arr[j+1] = tmp;\n                }\n    }\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        int[] nums = {64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90};\n        System.out.println(\"Unsorted: \" + Arrays.toString(nums));\n        System.out.println(\"Linear(25): index \" + linearSearch(nums, 25));\n        bubbleSort(nums);\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted  : \" + Arrays.toString(nums));\n        System.out.println(\"Binary(25): index \" + binarySearch(nums, 25));\n        int[] arr2 = {5, 2, 8, 1, 9, 3};\n        Arrays.sort(arr2);\n        System.out.println(\"Arrays.sort: \" + Arrays.toString(arr2));\n        System.out.println(\"binarySearch(8): \" + Arrays.binarySearch(arr2, 8));\n    }\n}",
        "expectedOutput": "Unsorted: [64, 34, 25, 12, 22, 11, 90]\nLinear(25): index 2\nSorted  : [11, 12, 22, 25, 34, 64, 90]\nBinary(25): index 3\nArrays.sort: [1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 9]\nbinarySearch(8): 4"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "note",
      "data": {
        "content": "**Binary search only works on sorted arrays.** Always sort first. Use lo + (hi - lo) / 2 instead of (lo + hi) / 2 to avoid integer overflow when lo and hi are large values."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "warning",
      "data": {
        "content": "Arrays.sort() on primitives uses Dual-Pivot Quicksort — O(n²) worst case. Arrays.sort() on Object arrays uses TimSort — O(n log n) guaranteed and stable. For strictly worst-case guarantees on primitives, implement merge sort manually."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "quiz",
      "data": {
        "questionId": "q_java_dsa_arr_001",
        "questionText": "What is the time complexity of accessing an element by index in a Java array?",
        "questionType": "mcq",
        "options": [
          {
            "id": "a",
            "text": "O(n)",
            "correct": false
          },
          {
            "id": "b",
            "text": "O(log n)",
            "correct": false
          },
          {
            "id": "c",
            "text": "O(1)",
            "correct": true
          },
          {
            "id": "d",
            "text": "O(n²)",
            "correct": false
          }
        ],
        "explanation": "Array elements are stored contiguously in memory. The address of any element is computed directly: base_address + (index × element_size). This is constant-time regardless of array size."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "quiz",
      "data": {
        "questionId": "q_java_dsa_arr_002",
        "questionText": "What exception is thrown when you access arr[arr.length] in Java?",
        "questionType": "mcq",
        "options": [
          {
            "id": "a",
            "text": "NullPointerException",
            "correct": false
          },
          {
            "id": "b",
            "text": "ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException",
            "correct": true
          },
          {
            "id": "c",
            "text": "IndexOutOfBoundsException",
            "correct": false
          },
          {
            "id": "d",
            "text": "IllegalArgumentException",
            "correct": false
          }
        ],
        "explanation": "Valid indices are 0 to arr.length-1. arr[arr.length] is one past the end. Java throws ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException (a subclass of IndexOutOfBoundsException)."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "quiz",
      "data": {
        "questionId": "q_java_dsa_arr_003",
        "questionText": "What is the prerequisite for binary search to work correctly?",
        "questionType": "mcq",
        "options": [
          {
            "id": "a",
            "text": "Array must contain only integers",
            "correct": false
          },
          {
            "id": "b",
            "text": "Array must be sorted",
            "correct": true
          },
          {
            "id": "c",
            "text": "Array length must be a power of 2",
            "correct": false
          },
          {
            "id": "d",
            "text": "Array must have no duplicate values",
            "correct": false
          }
        ],
        "explanation": "Binary search repeatedly halves the search space by comparing the target to the middle element. This only works if the array is sorted — on an unsorted array it can miss elements entirely."
      }
    }
  ]
}

{
  "path": "java.dsa.arrays.multidimensional",
  "title": "Multidimensional & Jagged Arrays",
  "section": "dsa",
  "difficulty": "intermediate",
  "estimatedMins": 10,
  "tags": [
    "java",
    "dsa",
    "2d-array",
    "jagged",
    "matrix"
  ],
  "isDeepDive": true,
  "isPublished": true,
  "sortOrder": 1,
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "data": {
        "content": "Java supports multidimensional arrays as arrays of arrays. A 2D array int[][] grid is an array where each element is itself an int[]. This means rows can have different lengths — jagged arrays — something not possible in many other languages."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "concept_cards",
      "data": {
        "items": [
          {
            "icon": "🔲",
            "title": "Regular 2D",
            "desc": "int[][] grid = new int[3][4] — 3 rows, 4 columns each. grid[row][col] to access. grid.length = rows, grid[0].length = cols."
          },
          {
            "icon": "📐",
            "title": "Jagged Array",
            "desc": "Omit second dimension: int[][] tri = new int[3][]. Assign each row separately: tri[0] = new int[1]. Different row lengths allowed."
          },
          {
            "icon": "🧮",
            "title": "Matrix Ops",
            "desc": "Traversal is O(rows × cols). Matrix multiplication is O(n³). Nested loops: outer for row, inner for column."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "data": {
        "language": "java",
        "filename": "JaggedArray.java",
        "runnable": true,
        "snippet": "public class JaggedArray {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        int[][] matrix = {{1,2,3},{4,5,6},{7,8,9}};\n        System.out.println(\"matrix[1][2] = \" + matrix[1][2]);\n\n        // Jagged array\n        int[][] tri = new int[3][];\n        for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) tri[i] = new int[i + 1];\n        int val = 1;\n        for (int[] row : tri)\n            for (int j = 0; j < row.length; j++) row[j] = val++;\n\n        System.out.println(\"Jagged:\");\n        for (int[] row : tri) {\n            for (int v : row) System.out.print(v + \" \");\n            System.out.println();\n        }\n    }\n}",
        "expectedOutput": "matrix[1][2] = 6\nJagged:\n1 \n2 3 \n4 5 6 "
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "quiz",
      "data": {
        "questionId": "q_java_dsa_arr_2d_001",
        "questionText": "What does int[][] tri = new int[3][] create?",
        "questionType": "mcq",
        "options": [
          {
            "id": "a",
            "text": "A 3×3 square matrix filled with zeros",
            "correct": false
          },
          {
            "id": "b",
            "text": "A 3-row array where each row length is unset",
            "correct": true
          },
          {
            "id": "c",
            "text": "A compile error — second dimension required",
            "correct": false
          },
          {
            "id": "d",
            "text": "Three null references",
            "correct": false
          }
        ],
        "explanation": "Omitting the second dimension creates a jagged array skeleton — 3 null int[] references. You then assign each row: tri[0] = new int[1]; This allows rows of different lengths."
      }
    }
  ]
}

{
  "path": "java.dsa.linkedlist",
  "title": "Linked List",
  "section": "dsa",
  "difficulty": "intermediate",
  "estimatedMins": 12,
  "tags": [
    "java",
    "dsa",
    "linkedlist"
  ],
  "isPublished": true,
  "sortOrder": 2,
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "data": {
        "content": "A linked list is a linear data structure where elements (nodes) are not stored in contiguous memory. Each node contains data and a pointer to the next node."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "concept_cards",
      "data": {
        "items": [
          {
            "icon": "🔗",
            "title": "Node",
            "desc": "Each node holds data and a reference (next) to the next node. Last node's next is null."
          },
          {
            "icon": "⚡",
            "title": "O(1) Insert",
            "desc": "Insert at head or after a known node is O(1) — just update pointers. No shifting like arrays."
          },
          {
            "icon": "🔍",
            "title": "O(n) Search",
            "desc": "No random access. Must traverse from head to find element. O(n) for get by index."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "quiz",
      "data": {
        "questionId": "q_java_dsa_ll_001",
        "questionText": "What is the time complexity of inserting at the head of a singly linked list?",
        "questionType": "mcq",
        "options": [
          {
            "id": "a",
            "text": "O(n)",
            "correct": false
          },
          {
            "id": "b",
            "text": "O(log n)",
            "correct": false
          },
          {
            "id": "c",
            "text": "O(1)",
            "correct": true
          },
          {
            "id": "d",
            "text": "O(n²)",
            "correct": false
          }
        ],
        "explanation": "Inserting at the head only requires updating the new node's next pointer and the head pointer — constant time regardless of list size."
      }
    }
  ]
}

